<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910614-0009</DOCNO><DOCID>910614-0009.</DOCID><HL>   Business Brief -- Seattle Silicon Corp.:   Firm Discloses Discussions   On Sale of Tool Division</HL><DATE>06/14/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION</SO><CO>   J.OKI</CO><MS>TECHNOLOGY (TEC)</MS><IN>COMMUNICATIONS TECHNOLOGY (CMT)SEMICONDUCTORS, INTEGRATED CHIPS (SEM)SOFTWARE (SOF)TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)INTERNATIONAL TRADE NEWS (TRD)</IN><NS>ACQUISITIONS andamp; MERGERS, TAKEOVERS, BOARD BATTLES (TNM)TRADE ISSUES (TRD)</NS><GV>FEDERAL GOVERNMENT (FDL)</GV><RE>FAR EAST (FE)JAPAN (JA)NORTH AMERICA (NME)PACIFIC RIM (PRM)UNITED STATES (US)WASHINGTON (WA)</RE><LP>   Seattle Silicon Corp. said it is discussing the possiblesale of its tool division to Oki Electric Industry Co., amajor Japanese producer of telecommunications andinformation-processing systems.   The Bellevue, Wash., company issued a statement aftercertain U.S. lawmakers questioned the soundness of the Bushadministration's decision to allow the transaction to takeplace. The company said it licenses its products to a&quot;limited&quot; number of defense contractors, but added that U.S.authorities no longer require licenses for those products tobe exported to either Japan or Western Europe.</LP><TEXT>   The tool division, which accounts for two-thirds ofSeattle Silicon's personnel, develops and markets computersoftware used in the design of semiconductors. The companysaid Oki has been a user of the software since 1987.   The company said a federal investment review panelrecently concluded that it had no objection to thetransaction. Both parties reaffirmed their intention tocomply with all U.S. export laws, the company said.</TEXT></DOC>